  "category": "governance",
  "title": "The Output Trace Is the Audit Trail You Own",
  "content": "Week 6 of the AI governance pilot puts a discipline in writing that the AI Fluency Framework names but rarely operationalizes: Transparency Diligence — taking accountability for the final product. The pilot hub's worked example shows a success coach editing a Claude-drafted email before it goes to a student. Claude got the policy correct. The coach rewrote the opening as a personal check-in, softened the deadline language, added two specific actions for that week, and included a direct phone number. The version that went out was a hybrid the coach owned.\n\nThose edits are the audit trail. Claude Enterprise's audit log captures platform-level events: who used the system, when, for how long. It does not reveal what specific conversations contained, and it does not capture what staff changed before sending an output externally. That gap is where Transparency Diligence lives. The output trace is the only record of what the human caught, what the human added, and what the human is accountable for.\n\nThe Week 6 challenge formalizes the practice. Pull one external output from the week. Document three things: what Claude produced, what you changed before you sent it, and why. The \"why\" carries the weight. \"Tone felt clinical\" tests Discernment. \"Policy was right but next steps were generic\" tests Description. \"Removed a student identifier from an example I was reusing\" tests the data classification framework. Each \"why\" maps to a competency the pilot is building.\n\nThis week's Governance Pulse depends on the trace. The teach-back works when you have a recent example of how you applied the four tiers. The trace gives you that example.",
  "tryThis": "Open the most recent external email or document where you used Claude this week. In a one-page note, capture three rows: what Claude produced, what you changed before you sent it, and why. Save it in your pilot folder. Bring one row to the Friday session and explain which of the 4Ds — Delegation, Description, Discernment, or Diligence — that edit was practicing.",
  "date": "2026-05-13",
  "publishedDate": "2026-05-13",
  "resource": "https://dccapinnovation.org/pilot_hub.html#week-6-7",
  "sourceNotes": "Claim: Week 6 puts Transparency Diligence in writing as a Week 6 discipline | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Week 6 \"Worked Example: An Output Trace\" closing line \"That division of labor is Diligence — knowing what's yours to own in every AI-assisted output.\"; ai_fluency_framework.html 4Ds section, Diligence card with \"Transparency Diligence\" sub-competency \"Transparency and accountability when distributing end products\")\nClaim: Worked example shows a success coach editing a Claude-drafted email to a student with at-risk renewal | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html \"Worked Example: An Output Trace\" task description: \"A success coach needs to email a student whose scholarship renewal is at risk because they're under-enrolled this semester.\")\nClaim: Claude produced correct policy info, clear deadline, professional tone | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html \"What Claude Produced\" panel verbatim: \"Correct policy information, clear deadline, professional tone.\")\nClaim: Coach rewrote opening as personal check-in, softened deadline, added two specific actions, included direct phone number | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html \"What Was Actually Sent\" panel verbatim language)\nClaim: Claude Enterprise audit log captures platform-level events but does not reveal conversation contents | Source: GROUNDED (ai_governance_framework.html Section 4 Security & Compliance Configuration, Audit Logging row: \"Enabled, reviewed monthly. Provides visibility into platform usage. Supports compliance documentation. Does not reveal information about specific conversations.\")\nClaim: Week 6 challenge asks for an output trace of one external output, capturing what Claude produced, what was changed, and why | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Week 6 Challenge box verbatim: \"Find one output you sent externally this week. Trace it like the example above: what did Claude produce, what did you change, and why? Bring the trace to Friday.\")\nClaim: Mapping \"why\" categories to specific 4D competencies (tone → Discernment, next-steps generic → Description, identifier removal → data classification framework) | Source: Editorial (analytical mapping of representative \"why\" notes to the 4Ds defined in ai_fluency_framework.html and the four-tier framework in ai_governance_framework.html Data Classification section)\nClaim: Week 6 Governance Pulse is the four-tier data classification teach-back | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Governance Pulse callout for Week 6-7: \"Teach-back: explain the 4-tier data classification to a colleague who is not in the pilot. If you can't explain it clearly, revisit the framework.\")",
